b|url=https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/rfc6810/|title=RFC 6810 - The Resource Public Key Infrastructure (RPKI) to Router Protocol|website=datatracker.ietf.org}}</ref> [[Cisco Systems]] offers native support on many platforms<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ripe.net/lir-services/resource-management/certification/router-configuration#Cisco|title=RPKI Configuration with Cisco IOS|work=[[RIPE]]}}</ref> for fetching the RPKI data set and using it in the router configuration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/iproute_bgp/command/irg-cr-book/bgp-m1.html|title=Cisco IOS IP Routing: BGP Command Reference - BGP Commands: M through N [Support]|website=Cisco}}</ref> Juniper offers support on all platforms<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.juniper.net/documentation/en_US/junos12.2/topics/topic-map/bgp-origin-as-validation.html|title=Example: Configuring Origin Validation for BGP - Technical Documentation - Support - Juniper Networks|website=www.juniper.net}}</ref> that run version 12.2 or newer. [[Quagga (software)|Quagga]] obtains this functionality through BGP Secure Routing Extensions (BGP-SRx)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nist.gov/services-resources/software/bgp-secure-routing-extension-bgp-srx-prototype|title=BGP Secure Routing Extension (BGP\u2011SRx) Prototype|date=August 15, 2016|website=NIST}}</ref> or a RPKI implementation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/rtrlib/quagga-rtrlib|title=Quagga with RPKI-RTR prefix origin validation support: rtrlib/quagga-rtrlib|date=May 10, 2019|via=GitHub}}</ref> fully RFC-compliant based on RTRlib. The RTRlib<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://rpki.realmv6.org/|title=RTRlib - The RPKI RTR Client C Library|website=rpki.realmv6.org}}</ref> provides an open source C implementation of the RTR protocol and prefix origin verification. The library is useful for developers of routing software but also for network operators.<ref>M. W\u00e4hlisch, F. Holler, T.C. Schmidt, J.H. Schiller: \"RTRlib: An Open-Source Library in C for RPKI-based Prefix Origin Validation, ''Proc. of USENIX Security Workshop CSET'13'', Berkeley, CA, USA:USENIX Assoc., 2013.</ref> Developers can integrate the RTRlib into the BGP daemon to extend their implementation towards RPKI. Network operators may use the RTRlib to develop monitoring tools (e.g., to check the proper operation of caches or to evaluate their performance).\n\nRFC 6494 updates the certificate validation method of the [[Secure Neighbor Discovery]] protocol (SEND) security mechanisms for [[Neighbor Discovery Protocol]] (ND) to use RPKI for use in IPv6. It defines a SEND certificate profile utilizing a modified RFC 6487 RPKI certificate profile which must include a single RFC 3779 IP address delegation extension.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://isbgpsafeyet.com/] Tool provided by Cloudflare to test if ISP is doeing RPKI validation\n* [https://rpki.readthedocs.io/ Open source RPKI Documentation]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140324124241/http://isoc.org/wp/ietfjournal/?p=2438 IETF Journal - Securing BGP and SIDR]\n* [http://rpki.net/ An open source implementation of the complete set of RPKI protocols and tools]\n* [http://rpki.realmv6.org/ RTRlib - Open source RPKI-Router Client C Library]\n* [https://nlnetlabs.nl/projects/rpki/about/ NLnet Labs open source RPKI tools developed in Rust]\n* [https://github.com/rtrlib/quagga-rtrlib Quagga RPKI implementation]\n* [http://www-x.antd.nist.gov/bgpsrx/ BGP-SrX - Quagga router implementation of RPKI-based Origin and Path validation.]\n* [http://rpki-monitor.antd.nist.gov/ RPKI-Monitor - Global and regional monitoring and analysis of RPKI deployment and use.]\n* [http://certification-stats.ripe.net/ RPKI Deployment statistics for all RIRs]\n* [http://www.labs.lacnic.net/~rpki/rpki-heatmaps/latest/global-roa-heatmap.png Global ROA deployment heatmap]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120404014109/http://rpki01.fra2.de.euro-transit.net/ EuroTransit GmbH RPKI Testbed