{"title_page": "Connecticut Public Radio", "text_new": "{{short description|Public radio network in Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = Connecticut Public Radio\n| image              = Connecticut Public Radio (WNPR) Logo.png\n| city               = \n| area               = [[Connecticut]]<br />[[Western Massachusetts]]<br />[[East End (Long Island)|Eastern Long Island]]\n| branding           = WNPR\n| slogan             = \n| frequency          = [[#Stations|See &sect; Stations]]\n| translator         = [[#Translator|See &sect; Translator]]\n| repeater           = \n| airdate            = June 1978\n| share              =\n| share as of        =\n| share source       =\n| format             = News/Talk ([[Public radio]])\n| language           = \n| power              =\n| erp                = \n| haat               = \n| class              = \n| facility_id        = \n| coordinates        = \n| callsign_meaning   = \n| former_callsigns   = \n| former_frequencies =\n| affiliations       = [[NPR]], [[American Public Media]], [[Public Radio International]]\n| owner              = [[Connecticut Public Broadcasting]]\n| licensee           =\n| sister_stations    =\n| webcast            = [http://stream.wnpr.org stream.wnpr.org] \n| website            = {{URL|www.wnpr.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Connecticut Public Radio''' is a network of [[Public broadcasting|public radio]] stations in the state of [[Connecticut]], [[western Massachusetts]], and [[East End (Long Island)|eastern Long Island]], affiliated with [[NPR]] (National Public Radio). It is owned by Connecticut Public Broadcasting Network, which also owns [[Connecticut Public Television]].\n\nThe radio network airs primarily news and talk from NPR along with several locally produced programs. It is headquartered with CPTV in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], and operates an additional studio in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:CPTV and WNPR building in Hartford, Connecticut, 2009-09-02.jpg|thumb|180px|The headquarters of WNPR and CPTV in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n\nIn the early 1970s, [[WTIC (AM)|WTIC]] in Hartford dropped its longtime [[classical music]] format in favor of [[adult contemporary]] music, and sold its library to CPTV. Looking for a way to put the library to use, CPTV decided to get into radio. At the time, while Hartford got a fairly decent signal from [[WFCR]] in [[Amherst, Massachusetts]] and much of southwestern Connecticut was covered by [[WNYC|WNYC-AM-FM]] in [[New York City]], most of the rest of the state did not even get a grade B signal from an NPR station. New Haven, for instance, had to content itself with a translator of WFCR on 90.5 FM. Finding available frequencies proved difficult, however. In addition to the crowded state of the noncommercial end of the FM dial in the Northeast, there was a considerable glut of 10-watt stations in the state. Ultimately, CPTV bought the 90.5 frequency from the Friends of WFCR, the New Haven group that owned the WFCR translator, and used it as the linchpin for what would become Connecticut Public Radio.<ref name=CTMag>{{cite news|url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/Connecticut-Magazine/April-2013/CPTV-Celebrates-50-Years-Present-at-the-Creation |title=CPTV Celebrates 50 Years: Present at the Creation|last=Grandjean|first=Pat|work=[[Connecticut Magazine]] |date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe network's first station, '''WPBH''',<ref name=\"fccMeriden\" /> signed on in June 1978.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our History |url=http://www.cpbn.org/our-history |publisher=Connecticut Public Broadcasting Network |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> The station was licensed to [[Meriden, Connecticut|Meriden]], halfway between Hartford and New Haven, in order to serve both cities (Hartford and New Haven, then as now, are separate radio markets).  CPBI originally wanted the WNPR calls, but the FCC turned it down due to objections from [[WPLR]] in New Haven, who claimed the calls sounded too similar. It became '''WPKT''' in 1984<ref name=\"fccMeriden\" /> after board chairman Homer Babbidge requested the FCC change the call letters to honor CPBN head Paul K. Taff.\n\n'''WNPR''' (89.1 FM) in Norwich followed in 1981,<ref name=\"fccNorwich\" /> '''WEDW-FM''' (88.5 FM) in Stamford in 1985<ref name=\"fccStamford\" /> and '''WRLI-FM''' (91.3 FM) on Long Island in 1993.<ref name=\"fccLI\" />\n\nOn September 15, 2011, '''WPKT''' and '''WNPR''' swapped callsigns.<ref name=\"fccMeriden\" /><ref name=\"fccNorwich\" /> Although 90.5 FM has always been the [[Flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]], the network had been using WNPR as its on-air name since the 1990s.\n\nFor the first 20 years of its existence, the network broadcast a mix of classical music, jazz and NPR talk. However, starting in the late 1990s, WNPR began gradually increasing the news programming on its schedule. One of the first casualties of this change was the popular classical music program ''[[Morning pro musica]],'' which was fed from [[WGBH-FM]] in [[Boston]]. The program had aired on WNPR as part of the terms by which the Friends of WFCR sold the 90.5 frequency to CPBI. However, by the late 1990s, this resulted in WNPR only being able to run the first hour of ''[[Morning Edition]].'' Ultimately, WNPR decided to cancel ''Morning pro musica,'' even though network executives knew it would cause a major loss in funding, though the change of direction in news-heavy NPR member stations, especially after the [[September 11 attacks]] occurred, made the format change palatable.<ref name=CTMag/> Ultimately, in 2006, WNPR dropped classical music altogether in favor of a full-time news and information format. In 2013, the station launched a new online service, WNPR News.\n\n=== WAIC ===\n{{main|WAIC}}\nFrom 2011 to 2016, Connecticut Public Radio operated WAIC (91.9 FM), the college radio station of [[American International College]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]]. WAIC first went on air in February 1967, going stereo in 1985.  Initially programmed from American International College (at various points programming [[top 40]] and [[adult hits]]), it became a full-time relay of Connecticut Public Radio on November 1, 2011.<ref name=\"wnpr-wnpronwaic\">{{cite press release|title=WAIC and WNPR Launch Collaboration to Bring New Programming to the Springfield Market|publisher=Connecticut Public Broadcasting|date=November 1, 2011|url=http://www.cpbn.org/waic-and-wnpr-launch-collaboration-bring-new-programming-springfield-market|accessdate=November 2, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331220659/http://www.cpbn.org/waic-and-wnpr-launch-collaboration-bring-new-programming-springfield-market|archivedate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> This ended in 2016, when WNPR turned over operation of WAIC to [[WFCR]], the NPR member for Western Massachusetts. WFCR made WAIC a satellite of its all-news network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nepr.net/press-releases/2016/06/28/nepr-news-network-completed-with-full-fm-service-in-four-counties|title=NEPR News Network Completed With Full FM Service In Four Counties|publisher=New England Public Radio|date=2016-06-28}}</ref>\n\n== Programming ==\nWNPR features the programs ''[[Where We Live]]'', ''The Colin McEnroe Show'', ''The [[Faith Middleton]] Show'' and ''[[The Needle Drop]]''. All are based out of Hartford except ''The Faith Middleton Show'', which has been based at the New Haven studio since it first went on the air. The station also syndicates NPR programming.<ref>{{cite web |title=WNPR Program Listing |url=http://www.cpbn.org/programs/WNPR/list |publisher=Connecticut Public Broadcasting Network |accessdate=May 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501150902/http://www.cpbn.org/programs/WNPR/list |archivedate=May 1, 2013 }}</ref> WNPR also produces the regional news show ''Next'' for a group of northeast public radio stations.\n\nIn the aftermath of Hurricane Maria which hit Puerto Rico in September 2017, WNPR produced a documentary entitled \"The Island Next Door\", focused on the impact of the storm on the island and the links between New England and Puerto Rico. The documentary was released in late 2018 to coincide with the one year mark since the storm ravaged Puerto Rico.\n\n== Awards ==\nWNPR has received many awards over the past few decades. It has received two [[Peabody Award|George Foster Peabody Awards]], five Ohio State Awards and two [[Gracie Awards|Gracie Allen Awards.]] It has also gotten over 60 [[Associated Press]] Awards, which include eight [[Mark Twain Readers Award|Mark Twain Awards]] for Overall Station Excellence. \n\n[[Faith Middleton]] has been voted Best Radio Talk-Show Host by ''[[Connecticut Magazine]]'' readers for the past 10 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ctpublic.org/honors-awards-for-cpbn/|title=Honors & Awards for CPBN \u00b7 Connecticut Public|publisher=Connecticut Public|access-date=2018-09-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Stations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! [[Call signs in North America|Call sign]]\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | [[Frequency]]\n! [[City of license]]\n! [[Facility ID]]\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | [[Effective radiated power|ERP]]<br />[[watt|W]]\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | [[Height above average terrain|Height]]<br />[[Metre|m]] ([[Foot (unit)|ft]])\n! [[List of North American broadcast station classes|Class]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Transmitter coordinates\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Call sign meaning\n|-\n| {{rh}} | WEDW-FM || 88.5 FM || [[Stamford, Connecticut]] || 13619 || 2,000 || {{Convert|92|m|ft|sp=us}} || A || {{Coord|41|02|49|N|73|31|36|W|type:landmark_region:US-CT_source:FCC|name=WEDW-FM}} || \n|- style=\"border: 2px solid #00f;\"\n| {{rh}} | WNPR || 90.5 FM ([[HD Radio|HD]]) || [[Meriden, Connecticut]] || 13627 || 18,500 || {{Convert|251|m|ft|sp=us}} || B || {{Coord|41|33|42|N|72|50|41|W|type:landmark_region:US-CT_source:FCC|name=WNPR|display=inline,title}} || '''N'''orwich '''P'''ublic '''R'''adio<ref name=\"callorig\" />\n|-\n| {{rh}} | WPKT || 89.1 FM ([[HD Radio|HD]]) || [[Norwich, Connecticut]] || 13618 || 5,100 || {{Convert|180|m|ft|sp=us}} || B1 || {{Coord|41|31|11|N|72|10|4|W|type:landmark_region:US-CT_source:FCC|name=WPKT}} || '''P'''aul '''K''' '''T'''aff\n|-\n| {{rh}} | WRLI-FM || 91.3 FM || [[Southampton (village), New York|Southampton, New York]] || 13598 || 10,000 || {{Convert|95|m|ft|sp=us}} || B1 || {{Coord|40|56|5|N|72|23|15|W|type:landmark_region:US-NY_source:FCC|name=WRLI-FM}} || '''R'''adio '''L'''ong '''I'''sland\n|}\n\n=== Translator ===\n{{RadioTranslators\n| callsign = WNPR\n\n| call1    = W258AC\n| freq1    = 99.5\n| watts1   = 10\n| haat1    = 117\n| class1   = D\n| city1    = Storrs, Connecticut\n\n| call2    = W206BW\n| freq2    = 89.1\n| watts2   = 10\n| haat2    = 53\n| class2   = D\n| city2    = Westville, Connecticut\n}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n\n=== Other stations ===\n* [[WECS]] (90.1 FM) [[Windham, Connecticut|Windham]]: [[Eastern Connecticut State University]]'s campus station simulcasts the network's feeds of ''[[Morning Edition]]'', ''[[All Things Considered]]'' and ''[[Car Talk]]''.\n* [[WVOF]] (88.5 FM) [[Fairfield, Connecticut|Fairfield]]: [[Fairfield University]]'s campus station simulcasts the network's feeds of ''[[Morning Edition]]'', ''[[All Things Considered]]'', ''[[Where We Live]]'', ''[[Car Talk]]'', ''[[Wait, Wait Don't Tell Me]]'', ''Living on Earth'', ''Speaking of Faith'', ''Studio 360''. and the [[BBC World Service]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnpr.org/about-wnpr-0}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Connecticut}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"callorig\">{{cite web |url=http://nelson.oldradio.com/origins.call-list.html |title=Call Letter Origins |publisher=Radio History on the Web |accessdate=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218013408/http://nelson.oldradio.com/origins.call-list.html |archivedate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"fccMeriden\">{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |work=CDBS Public Access Database |title=WNPR Call Sign History |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=13627&Callsign=WNPR |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"fccNorwich\">{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |work=CDBS Public Access Database |title=WPKT Call Sign History |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=13618&Callsign=WPKT |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"fccStamford\">{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |work=CDBS Public Access Database |title=WEDW-FM Call Sign History |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=13619&Callsign=WEDW-FM |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"fccLI\">{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |work=CDBS Public Access Database |title=WRLI-FM Call Sign History |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=13598&Callsign=WRLI-FM |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|www.wnpr.org|WNPR News}}\n{{FM station data|WNPR}}\n=== Other stations ===\n{{FM station data|WEDW}}\n{{FM station data|WPKT}}\n{{FM station data|WRLI}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Radio Stations\n| list  =\n{{Hartford Radio}}\n{{New Haven Radio}}\n{{New London Radio}}\n{{Stamford-Norwalk Radio}}\n{{Long Island Radio}}\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n{{Public_broadcasting_in_the_United_States}}\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = NPR Member Stations\n| list  =\n{{NPR Connecticut}}\n{{NPR New York}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Connecticut|*]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in New York (state)|*]]\n[[Category:American International College]]\n[[Category:HD Radio stations]]\n[[Category:Media in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Media in Suffolk County, New York]]\n[[Category:NPR member networks]]\n[[Category:NPR member stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public radio network in Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name               = Connecticut Public Radio\n| image              = Connecticut Public Radio (WNPR) Logo.png\n| city               = \n| area               = [[Connecticut]]<br />[[Western Massachusetts]]<br />[[East End (Long Island)|Eastern Long Island]]\n| branding           = WNPR\n| slogan             = \n| frequency          = [[#Stations|See &sect; Stations]]\n| translator         = [[#Translator|See &sect; Translator]]\n| repeater           = \n| airdate            = June 1978\n| share              =\n| share as of        =\n| share source       =\n| format             = News/Talk ([[Public radio]])\n| language           = \n| power              =\n| erp                = \n| haat               = \n| class              = \n| facility_id        = \n| coordinates        = \n| callsign_meaning   = \n| former_callsigns   = \n| former_frequencies =\n| affiliations       = [[NPR]], [[American Public Media]], [[Public Radio International]]\n| owner              = [[Connecticut Public Broadcasting]]\n| licensee           =\n| sister_stations    =\n| webcast            = [http://stream.wnpr.org stream.wnpr.org] \n| website            = {{URL|www.wnpr.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Connecticut Public Radio''' is a network of [[Public broadcasting|public radio]] stations in the state of [[Connecticut]], [[western Massachusetts]], and [[East End (Long Island)|eastern Long Island]], affiliated with [[NPR]] (National Public Radio). It is owned by Connecticut Public Broadcasting Network, which also owns [[Connecticut Public Television]].\n\nThe radio network airs primarily news and talk from NPR along with several locally produced programs. It is headquartered with CPTV in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], and operates an additional studio in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:CPTV and WNPR building in Hartford, Connecticut, 2009-09-02.jpg|thumb|180px|The headquarters of WNPR and CPTV in Hartford, Connecticut]]\n\nIn the early 1970s, [[WTIC (AM)|WTIC]] in Hartford dropped its longtime [[classical music]] format in favor of [[adult contemporary]] music, and sold its library to CPTV. Looking for a way to put the library to use, CPTV decided to get into radio. At the time, while Hartford got a fairly decent signal from [[WFCR]] in [[Amherst, Massachusetts]] and much of southwestern Connecticut was covered by [[WNYC|WNYC-AM-FM]] in [[New York City]], most of the rest of the state did not even get a grade B signal from an NPR station. New Haven, for instance, had to content itself with a translator of WFCR on 90.5 FM. Finding available frequencies proved difficult, however. In addition to the crowded state of the noncommercial end of the FM dial in the Northeast, there was a considerable glut of 10-watt stations in the state. Ultimately, CPTV bought the 90.5 frequency from the Friends of WFCR, the New Haven group that owned the WFCR translator, and used it as the linchpin for what would become Connecticut Public Radio.<ref name=CTMag>{{cite news|url=http://www.connecticutmag.com/Connecticut-Magazine/April-2013/CPTV-Celebrates-50-Years-Present-at-the-Creation |title=CPTV Celebrates 50 Years: Present at the Creation|last=Grandjean|first=Pat|work=[[Connecticut Magazine]] |date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe network's first station, '''WPBH''',<ref name=\"fccMeriden\" /> signed on in June 1978.<ref>{{cite web |title=Our History |url=http://www.cpbn.org/our-history |publisher=Connecticut Public Broadcasting Network |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> The station was licensed to [[Meriden, Connecticut|Meriden]], halfway between Hartford and New Haven, in order to serve both cities (Hartford and New Haven, then as now, are separate radio markets).  CPBI originally wanted the WNPR calls, but the FCC turned it down due to objections from [[WPLR]] in New Haven, who claimed the calls sounded too similar. It became '''WPKT''' in 1984<ref name=\"fccMeriden\" /> after board chairman Homer Babbidge requested the FCC change the call letters to honor CPBN head Paul K. Taff.\n\n'''WNPR''' (89.1 FM) in Norwich followed in 1981,<ref name=\"fccNorwich\" /> '''WEDW-FM''' (88.5 FM) in Stamford in 1985<ref name=\"fccStamford\" /> and '''WRLI-FM''' (91.3 FM) on Long Island in 1993.<ref name=\"fccLI\" />\n\nOn September 15, 2011, '''WPKT''' and '''WNPR''' swapped callsigns.<ref name=\"fccMeriden\" /><ref name=\"fccNorwich\" /> Although 90.5 FM has always been the [[Flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]], the network had been using WNPR as its on-air name since the 1990s.\n\nFor the first 20 years of its existence, the network broadcast a mix of classical music, jazz and NPR talk. However, starting in the late 1990s, WNPR began gradually increasing the news programming on its schedule. One of the first casualties of this change was the popular classical music program ''[[Morning pro musica]],'' which was fed from [[WGBH-FM]] in [[Boston]]. The program had aired on WNPR as part of the terms by which the Friends of WFCR sold the 90.5 frequency to CPBI. However, by the late 1990s, this resulted in WNPR only being able to run the first hour of ''[[Morning Edition]].'' Ultimately, WNPR decided to cancel ''Morning pro musica,'' even though network executives knew it would cause a major loss in funding, though the change of direction in news-heavy NPR member stations, especially after the [[September 11 attacks]] occurred, made the format change palatable.<ref name=CTMag/> Ultimately, in 2006, WNPR dropped classical music altogether in favor of a full-time news and information format. In 2013, the station launched a new online service, WNPR News.\n\n=== WAIC ===\n{{main|WAIC}}\nFrom 2011 to 2016, Connecticut Public Radio operated WAIC (91.9 FM), the college radio station of [[American International College]] in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]]. WAIC first went on air in February 1967, going stereo in 1985.  Initially programmed from American International College (at various points programming [[top 40]] and [[adult hits]]), it became a full-time relay of Connecticut Public Radio on November 1, 2011.<ref name=\"wnpr-wnpronwaic\">{{cite press release|title=WAIC and WNPR Launch Collaboration to Bring New Programming to the Springfield Market|publisher=Connecticut Public Broadcasting|date=November 1, 2011|url=http://www.cpbn.org/waic-and-wnpr-launch-collaboration-bring-new-programming-springfield-market|accessdate=November 2, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331220659/http://www.cpbn.org/waic-and-wnpr-launch-collaboration-bring-new-programming-springfield-market|archivedate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> This ended in 2016, when WNPR turned over operation of WAIC to [[WFCR]], the NPR member for Western Massachusetts. WFCR made WAIC a satellite of its all-news network.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nepr.net/press-releases/2016/06/28/nepr-news-network-completed-with-full-fm-service-in-four-counties|title=NEPR News Network Completed With Full FM Service In Four Counties|publisher=New England Public Radio|date=2016-06-28}}</ref>\n\n== Programming ==\nWNPR features the programs ''[[Where We Live]]'', ''The Colin McEnroe Show'', ''The [[Faith Middleton]] Show'' and ''[[The Needle Drop]]''. All are based out of Hartford except ''The Faith Middleton Show'', which has been based at the New Haven studio since it first went on the air. The station also syndicates NPR programming.<ref>{{cite web |title=WNPR Program Listing |url=http://www.cpbn.org/programs/WNPR/list |publisher=Connecticut Public Broadcasting Network |accessdate=May 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501150902/http://www.cpbn.org/programs/WNPR/list |archivedate=May 1, 2013 }}</ref> WNPR also produces the regional news show ''Next'' for a group of northeast public radio stations.\n\nIn the aftermath of Hurricane Maria which hit Puerto Rico in September 2017, WNPR produced a documentary entitled \"The Island Next Door\", focused on the impact of the storm on the island and the links between New England and Puerto Rico. The documentary was released in late 2018 to coincide with the one year mark since the storm ravaged Puerto Rico.\n\n== Awards ==\nWNPR has received many awards over the past few decades. It has received two [[Peabody Award|George Foster Peabody Awards]], five Ohio State Awards and two [[Gracie Awards|Gracie Allen Awards.]] It has also gotten over 60 [[Associated Press]] Awards, which include eight [[Mark Twain Readers Award|Mark Twain Awards]] for Overall Station Excellence. \n\n[[Faith Middleton]] has been voted Best Radio Talk-Show Host by ''[[Connecticut Magazine]]'' readers for the past 10 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ctpublic.org/honors-awards-for-cpbn/|title=Honors & Awards for CPBN \u00b7 Connecticut Public|publisher=Connecticut Public|access-date=2018-09-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Stations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! [[Call signs in North America|Call sign]]\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | [[Frequency]]\n! [[City of license]]\n! [[Facility ID]]\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | [[Effective radiated power|ERP]]<br />[[watt|W]]\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | [[Height above average terrain|Height]]<br />[[Metre|m]] ([[Foot (unit)|ft]])\n! [[List of North American broadcast station classes|Class]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Transmitter coordinates\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Call sign meaning\n|-\n| {{rh}} | WEDW-FM || 88.5 FM || [[Stamford, Connecticut]] || 13619 || 2,000 || {{Convert|92|m|ft|sp=us}} || A || {{Coord|41|02|49|N|73|31|36|W|type:landmark_region:US-CT_source:FCC|name=WEDW-FM}} || \n|- style=\"border: 2px solid #00f;\"\n| {{rh}} | WNPR || 90.5 FM ([[HD Radio|HD]]) || [[Meriden, Connecticut]] || 13627 || 18,500 || {{Convert|251|m|ft|sp=us}} || B || {{Coord|41|33|42|N|72|50|41|W|type:landmark_region:US-CT_source:FCC|name=WNPR|display=inline,title}} || '''N'''orwich '''P'''ublic '''R'''adio<ref name=\"callorig\" />\n|-\n| {{rh}} | WPKT || 89.1 FM ([[HD Radio|HD]]) || [[Norwich, Connecticut]] || 13618 || 5,100 || {{Convert|180|m|ft|sp=us}} || B1 || {{Coord|41|31|11|N|72|10|4|W|type:landmark_region:US-CT_source:FCC|name=WPKT}} || '''P'''aul '''K''' '''T'''aff\n|-\n| {{rh}} | WRLI-FM || 91.3 FM || [[Southampton (village), New York|Southampton, New York]] || 13598 || 10,000 || {{Convert|95|m|ft|sp=us}} || B1 || {{Coord|40|56|5|N|72|23|15|W|type:landmark_region:US-NY_source:FCC|name=WRLI-FM}} || '''R'''adio '''L'''ong '''I'''sland\n|}\n\n=== Translator ===\n{{RadioTranslators\n| callsign = WNPR\n\n| call1    = W258AC\n| freq1    = 99.5\n| watts1   = 10\n| haat1    = 117\n| class1   = D\n| city1    = Storrs, Connecticut\n\n| call2    = W206BW\n| freq2    = 89.1\n| watts2   = 10\n| haat2    = 53\n| class2   = D\n| city2    = Westville, Connecticut\n}}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n\n=== Other stations ===\n* [[WECS]] (90.1 FM) [[Windham, Connecticut|Windham]]: [[Eastern Connecticut State University]]'s campus station simulcasts the network's feeds of ''[[Morning Edition]]'', ''[[All Things Considered]]'' and ''[[Car Talk]]''.\n* [[WVOF]] (88.5 FM) [[Fairfield, Connecticut|Fairfield]]: [[Fairfield University]]'s campus station simulcasts the network's feeds of ''[[Morning Edition]]'', ''[[All Things Considered]]'', ''[[Where We Live]]'', ''[[Car Talk]]'', ''[[Wait, Wait Don't Tell Me]]'', ''Living on Earth'', ''Speaking of Faith'', ''Studio 360''. and the [[BBC World Service]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnpr.org/about-wnpr-0}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Connecticut}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"callorig\">{{cite web |url=http://nelson.oldradio.com/origins.call-list.html |title=Call Letter Origins |publisher=Radio History on the Web |accessdate=May 3, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218013408/http://nelson.oldradio.com/origins.call-list.html |archivedate=February 18, 2016 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"fccMeriden\">{{cit