 FM\n|[[KPRH]] \n|News\n|-\n|<small>''[[Ouray, Colorado|Ouray]]''</small>\n|<small>''91.5 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K218BE ([[KPRN]])''</small>\n|<small>''News''</small>\n|-\n|<small>''[[Parachute, Colorado|Parachute]]''</small>\n|<small>''88.3 FM''</small> \n|<small>''K202BI ([[KPRN]])''</small>\n|<small>''News''</small>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Pueblo, Colorado|Pueblo]]\n|1230 AM\n|[[KKPC]] \n|News\n|-\n|<small>''101.9 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K270CM ([[KKPC]])''</small>\n|<small>''News''</small>\n|-\n|91.9 FM \n|[[KCFP]] \n|Classical\n|-\n|<small>''[[Rangely, Colorado|Rangely]]''</small>\n|<small>''91.1 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K216BO ([[KPRN]])''</small>\n|<small>''News''</small>\n|-\n|<small>''[[Old Snowmass, Colorado|Old Snowmass]]''</small>\n|<small>''93.9 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K234BJ ([[KVOV]])''</small>\n|<small>''Classical''</small>\n|-\n|<small>''[[Thomasville, Colorado|Thomasville]]''</small>\n|<small>''93.7 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K229AI ([[KVOV]])''</small>\n|<small>''Classical''</small>\n|-\n|[[Vail, Colorado|Vail]]\n|89.9 FM\n|[[KPRE]]\n|''News''\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n== External links ==\n* [http://www.cpr.org/ Colorado Public Radio]\n \n{{Denver Radio}}\n{{NPR Colorado}}\n{{American broadcast radio}}\n{{Public_broadcasting_in_the_United_States}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Colorado|*]]\n[[Category:NPR member networks]]\n[[Category:Colorado Public Radio]]\n[[Category:American radio networks]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Broadcasting network\n|name           = Colorado Public Radio\n|logo           = \n|type           = [[Public broadcasting|Public radio network]]\n|branding       = \n|airdate        = \n|country        = {{USA}}\n|available      = \n|founded        = 1991\n|founder        =\n|slogan         = \n|motto          = \n|market_share   = \n|license_area   = \n|broadcast_area = {{flag|Colorado}}\n|area           = \n|erp            = \n|owner          = \n|key_people     = \n|foundation     = \n|launch_date    = \n|dissolved      = \n|former_names   = \n|digital        = \n|analog         = \n|servicename1   = \n|service1       = \n|servicename2   = \n|service2       = \n|servicename3   = \n|service3       = \n|servicename4   = \n|service4       = \n|callsigns      = \n|callsign_meaning = \n|former_callsigns = \n|affiliation    = [[National Public Radio]]\n|affiliates     = \n|groups         = \n|former_affiliations = \n|website        = [http://www.cpr.org/ www.cpr.org]\n|footnotes      = \n}}\n\n[[File:Colorado Public Radio.jpg|250px|thumbnail|right|The Colorado Public Radio studios in Centennial, Colorado.]]\n'''Colorado Public Radio''' (CPR) is a [[Public broadcasting|public radio]] [[state network]] based in [[Denver, Colorado]] that broadcasts three services:  [[All-news radio|news]], [[classical music]] and OpenAir, which plays [[adult album alternative]] music. CPR operates a 30-signal, statewide radio network accessible to 80 percent of Coloradans.<ref name=charitynavigator>{{cite web|title=Colorado Public Radio|url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=10362|website=Charity Navigator|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> As of 2013, CPR had 440,000 weekly listeners, 47,000 contributing members and annual revenue of $14 million.<ref name=charitynavigator/> In early March 2019, CPR acquired hyperlocal news site [https://denverite.com Denverite] from Spirited Media to bolster its web news coverage for locals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4343bd9786a54eb58fa7ec66c3ad09f4|title=Colorado Public Radio buying online news site Denverite|date=2019-03-06|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westword.com/news/inside-colorado-public-radios-purchase-of-denverite-11260260|title=Inside Colorado Public Radio's Purchase of Denverite|last=Roberts|first=Michael|date=2019-03-07|website=Westword|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/billy-penn/colorado-public-radio-to-acquire-denverite-from-spirited-media-7375b532db7c|title=Colorado Public Radio to acquire Denverite from Spirited Media|last=Krewson|first=Chris|date=2019-03-06|website=Medium|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/denver/news/2019/03/06/colorado-public-radio-denverite-purchase.html|title=Colorado Public Radio purchasing hyperlocal news site Denverite|last=Rose|first=Jonathan|date=2019-03-06|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://current.org/2019/03/colorado-public-radio-acquires-local-spirited-media-website/|title=Colorado Public Radio acquires local Spirited Media website|last=Falk|first=Tyler|date=2019-03-06|website=Current|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\nCPR is a [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]], 501(c)(3) organization. Private support from listeners, corporations, foundations and partners accounts for approximately 95 percent of CPR's total budget.\n\n==History==\nThe first station in what would become Colorado Public Radio,  [[KCFR]] (90.1 FM) in Denver, went on the air in 1970. The station was initially licensed to the [[University of Denver]]. In 1973, KCFR began carrying programming from [[National Public Radio]] (NPR), beginning with \"[[All Things Considered]].\" \"[[Morning Edition]]\" was added in 1979. More NPR programming was added the following year when the network began to distribute programming via satellite.\n\nKCFR separated from the University of Denver in 1984, becoming a community-licensed public radio station. That same year, [[KPRN]] in [[Grand Junction, Colorado|Grand Junction]] signed on the air. In 1991, KPRN merged with KCFR, forming the new entity Colorado Public Radio.  The original plan as proposed to the Western Slope listeners and the FCC during the license acquisition phase was to continue providing original localized programming for the needs of the Western Slope audience.  But despite protests from those listeners, within a few years the KPRN studios were closed, all volunteers and news staff positions were eliminated and it became a [[Broadcast relay station|satellite station]] of KCFR.<ref name=\"westword\">{{cite news\n | url=http://www.westword.com/music/feedback-5057557\n | title=Feedback - - Music - Denver\n | work=[[Westword]]\n | author=Michael Roberts\n | date=1997-06-12\n | accessdate=2013-08-12 }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | url=http://www.current.org/wp-content/themes/current/archive-site/radio/radio110kprn.html\n | title=Battle of Grand Junction, 1991\n | work=Current.org\n | author=Steve Behrens\n | date=1991-05-27\n | accessdate=2013-08-12\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20130813013737/http://www.current.org/wp-content/themes/current/archive-site/radio/radio110kprn.html\n | archive-date=2013-08-13\n | url-status=dead\n }}</ref>\n\nCPR added more satellite stations in the following years, including [[KPRE]] Vail in 1994, [[KCFP]] Pueblo in 1996 and [[KPRH]] Montrose in 1998. CPR also began adding other low-power translators, sometimes in competition with existing public radio stations.  Stations in other areas not served by CPR, like [[KDNK]] in Carbondale, complained that CPR would also send out fundraising solicitation letters to KDNK listeners leaving the impression that they could thank CPR for receiving popular [[National Public Radio|NPR]] programs like All Things Considered or Morning Edition, sometimes resulting in misdirected donations.<ref name=\"westword\"/>\n\nUntil 2001, CPR's format was a mix of NPR programming and [[classical music]].  However, in 1999, CPR bought Denver classical music station [[KVOD]], a prelude to providing both a 24-hour news format and a 24-hour classical format<ref>{{cite web|title=Application Search Details, File Number: BPED-19960926MD, KVOD|url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=232859|website=Federal Communications Commission|accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, CPR attempted to purchasing the University of Northern Colorado's FM station [[KUNC]] in a closed-door deal with then UNC President Hank Brown.  When the pending deal was announced to the public, irate devoted KUNC listeners immediately raised over $1,000,000 in a week of emergency fundraising as a successful counteroffer to CPR's, thus ending CPR's plans to acquire the KUNC radio network.\n\nIn 2001, [[KCFC]] Boulder, [[KKPC]] Pueblo and [[KPRU]] on the Western Slope joined the CPR network. In 2004, CPR brought [[KVOV]] in Glenwood Springs on the air as part of its statewide network. In 2008, CPR's news service moved to 90.1 FM, and 88.1 FM carried CPR's classical service in Denver. In 2011, CPR launched the new-music station OpenAir on [[KDCO (AM)|1340 AM as KVOQ]], and in 2015, OpenAir switched to broadcasting as [[KVOQ (FM)|KVOQ-FM]] on 102.3 FM in Denver/Boulder, and KVXQ (now Classical KVXO) on 88.3 FM in Fort Collins.\n\n== CPR News ==\nCPR News includes a locally produced program called \u201cColorado Matters,\u201d local newscasts throughout the day and national/international news from sources like NPR and the BBC. As of 2015, 13 signals broadcast CPR News throughout the state of Colorado. Over the years, Colorado Public Radio's newsroom has received a number of journalism awards, including [[Edward R. Murrow Award (Radio Television Digital News Association)|RTNDA Edward R. Murrow Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 Edward R. Murrow Awards| url=http://rtdna.org/content/2015_region_3_murrow_winners|website=Radio Television Digital News Association|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref> Public Radio News Directors Incorporated (PRNDI) Awards<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 PRNDI Award Winners Outdo Fierce Competition|url=http://prndi.org/post/2014-prndi-award-winners-outdo-fierce-competition|website=Public Radio News Digital Incorporated|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> and Colorado Broadcasters Association (CBA) Awards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colorado Broadcasters 2014 Certificates of Merit|url=http://www.coloradobroadcasters.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/2014-COM-for-web.pdf|website=Colorado Broadcasters Association|accessdate=23 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== ''The Taxman'' ==\nIn 2017, CPR produced a three-part podcast broadcast on the radio entitled ''The Taxman.'' Produced by Rachel Estabrook, Nathaniel Minor and Ben Markus, it gives the story about the Taxpayers Bill of Rights, or [[TABOR]], in Colorado. It follows the man who created it, [[Douglas Bruce]], and how it affected the state government. All three episodes were released on November 13, 2017, and narrated by Rachel Estabrook and Nathaniel Minor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://taxman.cpr.org/|title=How Douglas Bruce And The Taxpayer's Bill Of Rights Conquered Colorado|last=Markus|first=Nathaniel Minor, Rachel Estabrook, Ben|work=Colorado Public Radio|access-date=2017-11-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Stations==\n''*NOTE: Italics denote low-power [[Broadcast relay station|translator stations]]. Many of the listed translators are owned by county cooperatives, and may change stations or frequencies with little notice.''\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Location\n!Frequency\n![[Call sign]]\n!Format\n|-\n|<small>''[[Aspen, Colorado|Aspen]]''</small>\n|<small>''101.5 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K268BJ ([[KVOV]])''</small>\n|<small>''Classical''</small>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Boulder, Colorado|Boulder]]\n|1490 AM \n|[[KCFC]] \n|News\n|-\n|<small>''106.3 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K292GW ([[KCFC]])''</small>\n|<small>''News''</small>\n|-\n|<small>''99.9 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K260AL ([[KVOD]])''</small>\n|<small>''Classical''</small>\n|-\n|[[Carbondale, Colorado|Carbondale]]\n|90.5 FM\n|[[KVOV]] \n|Classical\n|-\n|<small>''[[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]]''</small>\n|<small>''94.7 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K234AJ ([[KCFP]])''</small>\n|<small>''Classical''</small>\n|-\n|<small>''[[Cortez, Colorado|Cortez]]''</small>\t\n|<small>''102.5 FM''</small>\n|<small>''K273AE ([[KVOD]])''</small>\n|<small>''Class